def hexbin(column):
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel("Outcome")
    plt.hexbin(data_frame[column], data_frame["Outcome"], gridsize = 5)

def scatter(column):
    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel("Outcome")
    plt.scatter(data_frame[column], data_frame["Outcome"])

def plot_information(column):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(11,4))
    hexbin(column)
    scatter(column)

for title in data_frame:
    plot_information(title)

Question 1¶

  • Use mean or mod for replacing NAN values :

This soloution is very easy to implement and output of that is nice. But in some cases we have more missing values and replacing that with mean or mod can not train our model more and doesn't give to us more data.

  • Delete col that contain many missing values:

It is used when we have a lot missing values and replacing with mean or mod is not efficient way. But in other hand it cause we lose some info.

def drop_cols(title):
    data_frame.drop(title, axis = 1, inplace = True)

droped_titles = ["DiabetesPedigreeFunction"]
for title in droped_titles:
    drop_cols(title)


def fill_nan_with_mean(col, with_ceil=False):
    mean_val = ceil(col.mean()) if with_ceil else col.mean()
    col.fillna(mean_val, inplace=True)

titles_fill_with_mean = ["Glucose", "BloodPressure", "SkinThickness", "Insulin", "BMI",]
for title in titles_fill_with_mean:
    fill_nan_with_mean(data_frame[title])
fill_nan_with_mean(data_frame["Age"])


def fill_nan_with_mod(col):
    col.fillna(col.mode()[0], inplace=True)

titles_fill_with_mod = ["Pregnancies"]
for title in titles_fill_with_mod:
    fill_nan_with_mod(data_frame[title])

Question 3¶

Normalization And Standardization:

We reduce the range of data values with these methods. so the scale of features doesn't affect our prediction.

Normalization : rescales the values into a range of (0,1).It is useful when we dont know about the distribution.

$X_{new} = (X - X_{min})/(X_{max} - X_{min})$

Standardization: rescales data to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.It is useful when the feature distribution is normal or Gaussian.

$X_{new} = (X - mean)/std$

Which one is better ? it depends to out application. A normalized dataset will always have values between 0 to 1. A standardized dataset have a mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1. There is no upper or lower bound for the max or min values.

According to have better output, we select Normalization because most of our features have not normal dist.

In [14]:
temp_outcome = data_frame["Outcome"]
normalized_data_frame = data_frame.apply(lambda col : col if isinstance(col[0], str) else (col - col.mean()) / col.std())
normalized_data_frame["Outcome"] = temp_outcome

Question 4¶

Categorical values:¶

There are a lot of ways to handle categorical features and in the below we enumerate some of that. It is very important to know that we don't handle all of this type of data in a way and select one of that depend of type of data. some of that are :

  • Nominal: In this way, classified traits take out of order different values. And features will have no numerical value. One-hot can be used for encryption in this way.
  • Binary: In this way, only zero and one can be give to classified features.
  • Ordinal: In this way, classified features can take in order different values.

According to values we have in dataset, we won't need any of this.

If we want to speed up the operation of prediction and modeling in faster way we can delete some of cols addition to col that have many missing values

We can delete some of cols that have less correlation to outcome like SkinThickness and BloodPressure. But for better accuracy we won't delete this cols.

Question 6¶

Data splitting (train, test, validation)¶

there is different ways such as:

  • Cross validation : In this way, we have to step.

first step :a part of the data is chosen as train and the rest is chosen as validation data.
second step : this definition is switched and the train part becomes the validation part.

  • Leave-percentage-out : In this way, we mark p percentage of the train_data as test part. After learning with the train part, we can test_data the learnings on the validation data. If all of this works output is not fine we repeat all of that.

  • holdout : use sklearn.train_test_split().

In [16]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay, accuracy_score
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn import tree

def plot_success_rate(actual_output, predict_output, title):
    matrix = confusion_matrix(actual_output, predict_output)
    cm_display = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix = matrix)
    accurancy = accuracy_score(actual_output, predict_output) * 100
    cm_display.plot()
    cm_display.ax_.set_title(f"{title} accurancy = {accurancy}%")

def predict_and_print_report(classfier, print_tree=False):
    classfier.fit(input_train, output_train)
    train_predict = classfier.predict(input_train)
    test_predict = classfier.predict(input_test)
    if print_tree:
        tree.plot_tree(classfier.fit(input_train, output_train))
    print(classification_report(output_train, train_predict))
    print(classification_report(output_test, test_predict))
    plot_success_rate(train_predict, output_train, 'train_maxtrix')
    plot_success_rate(test_predict, output_test, 'test_maxtrix')

K-Nearest-Neighbours¶

In [21]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

train_accuracy, test_accuracy = [], []
best_index, best_score = 1, 0
for i in range(1, 25):
    knn_classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = i)
    knn_classifier.fit(input_train, output_train)
    train_score = accuracy_score(output_train, knn_classifier.predict(input_train))
    test_score  = accuracy_score(output_test,  knn_classifier.predict(input_test))
    train_accuracy.append(train_score)
    test_accuracy.append(test_score)
    if best_score < test_score:
        best_index, best_score = i, test_score

print('best n for num of neighbors : ', best_index)
plt.plot(train_accuracy)
plt.plot(test_accuracy)
plt.legend(["train_accuracy", "test_accuracy"])

Use GridSearchCv to find best parameters¶

In [26]:
from numpy import logspace

gscv = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(),
                   param_grid = {
                                    'C'       : logspace(-3, 3, 7),
                                    'solver'  : ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear'],
                                },
                   scoring='accuracy',
                   cv=15)

gscv.fit(input_train,output_train)

print("Tuned Hyperparameters :", gscv.best_params_)

Tuned Hyperparameters : {'C': 1000.0, 'solver': 'newton-cg'}

Question 1¶

For calculate accuracy and other parameters we should use explanations that are discussed in class like tp, tn, fp, fn.

tn: The values which are actually negative and also predicted as negative.
fn: The values which are actually positive but predicted as negative.
fp: The values which are actually negative but predicted as positive.
tp: The values which are actually positive and predicted as positive too.

Question 2¶

Job has done.

Question 3¶

  • Overfitting : when the model fited on train data and performs very well on that but has not fine output for test data. In this case we modeled noise of train data.
  • Underfitting : when model has bad performance on both datasets (train data and test data)

Cause of use built in and libraries and set params on that we have less overfitting and underfitting.

Search best parameters for random forest¶

In [29]:
train_accuracy, test_accuracy = [], []
best_max_depth, best_score = 1, 0
for i in range(1, 50):
    forest_classifire = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth = i)
    forest_classifire.fit(input_train, output_train)
    train_score = accuracy_score(output_train, forest_classifire.predict(input_train))
    test_score  = accuracy_score(output_test,  forest_classifire.predict(input_test))
    train_accuracy.append(train_score)
    test_accuracy.append(test_score)
    if best_score < test_score:
        best_max_depth, best_score = i, test_score

print('best max_depth : ', best_max_depth)
plt.plot(train_accuracy)
plt.plot(test_accuracy)
plt.legend(["train_accuracy", "test_accuracy"])

Question 2¶

Bias and Variance relation

Bias : if our model systematically under or over predicts the target variable.
Variance : captures the generalizability of the model.
Best property : low bias and variance.
Random Forest employs to reduce variance in predicts with some of techniques. It does this mostly by averaging together a number trees that have very weakly correlation.

The result is fine and near to expectations
